                     What is this software?
                     ----------------------

Astarte is a multiparadigm programming language, and this 
software is an implementation of Astarte.  Documentation on
Astarte can be found at http://www.cs.ecu.edu/astarte.
The documentation is also distributed with this software in
the htdoc directory.

This software is provided as source code.  It currently runs only
under flavors of Unix, including Linux.  You will need a C
compiler to install it.  The GNU C compiler is recommended.
The C compiler should support ANSI C.
You will also need an implementation of the Unix make command.

This is a prerelease, not a finished product.  Modifications to both
the documentation and the implementation are frequent.

Please read the disclaimer and copyright in file COPYRIGHT.

                        To install Astarte
		     FOLLOW THESE INSTRUCTIONS!
                     -------------------------

1. Choose a directory to hold the installation.  A suggestion
   is /usr/local/lib/astarte.  Move this file and all of the
   directories that are with it to that directory.  You should
   have subdirectories
      ast/
      htdoc/
      messages/
      src/
      test/

2. If you choose a directory other than /usr/local/lib/astarte,
   then edit file src/misc/config.h.  Change the definition of 
   BASE_DIR to be the directory that contains this file and the
   directories ast, htdoc, messages, src and test.

3. Edit file src/exec/Makefile.  Change the definitions of
   TOPDIR and BINDIR if necessary.

     TOPDIR is the src directory.  If you install in /usr/local/lib/astarte,
            then TOPDIR should be /usr/local/lib/astarte/src.  

     BINDIR is the directories where the binaries should be put.
            For example, it might be /usr/local/bin.

   Be sure that BINDIR is in your path, to make it possible to run
   the compiler and interpreter.

   Also edit the definitions of SHELL, RM, MV, TOUCH and CC if necessary.
   Pay special attention to CC, which is the name of the C compiler that
   you will use.

4. Change to directory src/exec.  Type

     make install

   The compiler should be built.  

   If the make tries to run bison or flex, and you do not have bison 
   or flex, then touch files src/exec/parser.c and src/exec/lexer.c 
   to make their modification times later than other files.  
   For example, do
      cd src/exec
      touch parser.c lexer.c
   Be sure your system clock is not so far off that the new modification
   times are not later than the old ones.

5. Change do directory ast.  Type

     make all

   This should build the standard library. If you get any warning
   messages, ignore them.

6. Change to directory test, and do

     make all

   The tests should run.  There will be a lot of output.  The tests
   are currently not in very good shape, and you will get some complaints,
   possibly some about mismatches.  Do not worry about them.
   What you should NOT get is a compiler or interpreter abort/core dump.

7. After a successful installation, you can delete the src and
   test directories.  They are not used during execution.  Do not
   delete the ast or messages directories.



			INSTALLATION PROBLEMS
			---------------------

1. The makefile might try to rebuild the parser and lexer using bison
   and flex.  If you have bison and flex, that is fine.  If you do 
   not have them, then change directory to src/exec and touch
   each of parser.c and lexer.c.  (Use the touch command to set their
   modification times to the current time.)  The makefile should 
   no longer try to build the parser and lexer.

2. Some versions of make might terminate prematurely.  That is a
   problem with the system.  Try restarting the make.

3. If you get a link error complaining that alloca does not
   exist, edit file src/misc/unixs.h.  Find the line

   #define USE_ALLOCA

   and comment it out.  That should get rid of that problem.

4. If either the compiler or interpreter complain about being out
   of memory, or if the interpreter seems to get a lot of errors,
   try editing file src/misc/options.h.  

   Comment out the line that includes file unixs.h and instead 
   include unixl.h or unixm.h.  Those files set up memory 
   allocation differently.  After editing those files, 
   go to the src/exec directory, and type

     make clean
     make install
   
If you have any other problems, let me know by email (karl@cs.ecu.edu).
